lor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukhuldar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Khuldar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/24/02 7:51:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10182.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: 802.11 Wireless...</span><hr size=1> There are a few diferent kinds of 802.11.  the most common, 802.11b will give you about the same bandwith as if you were running through an old 10m shared hub.  It can also only support  around 10 connections at once, but due to the shared nature, it will be slow with that many.  If you are just looking to have one or two machines hanging off of one hub, you should be fine.  If you are looking for a more large scale deployment, there are a lot of issues with bandwith and overlaping chanels.<br>  As to a rip off or not, it's a question of what's important to you.  Do you want to play EQ anywhere in your house, at the cost of a few hundred bucks and slightly longer load times?  If you dial in to the internet via a modem, that's probably going to be the slow point on your network, not the wireless.<br>  I've not tried to play EQ over wireless, but use it a lot at work in a number of situations and my brother-in-law has a set up at his home which I use from time to time.  The flexability is very nice, and IMHO is worth the bandwith tradeoffs for normal use.  As for the pricetag?  It's a chunk to pay for what you get.  <br><br>Hope that helped<br>--Khuldar<br> <p><img src="http://www.skidmore.edu/~mhasselb/AM/Khuldarsig.jpg" border="0"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uojuillean.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ojuillean</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran